Note: ========================================
Note: x86-64 Assembly Lexer
Note: ========================================
Note: Lexer for x86-64 assembly language (AT&T syntax / GNU assembler)
Note: Part of the Translation translation system
Note: Token Types: Instructions, Registers, Directives, Labels, Numbers, Strings, Symbols
Note: ========================================

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

Constant TOKEN_INSTRUCTION as Integer is 1
Constant TOKEN_REGISTER as Integer is 2
Constant TOKEN_DIRECTIVE as Integer is 3
Constant TOKEN_LABEL as Integer is 4
Constant TOKEN_NUMBER as Integer is 5
Constant TOKEN_STRING as Integer is 6
Constant TOKEN_COMMA as Integer is 7
Constant TOKEN_LPAREN as Integer is 8
Constant TOKEN_RPAREN as Integer is 9
Constant TOKEN_DOLLAR as Integer is 10
Constant TOKEN_PERCENT as Integer is 11
Constant TOKEN_COLON as Integer is 12
Constant TOKEN_NEWLINE as Integer is 13
Constant TOKEN_IDENTIFIER as Integer is 14
Constant TOKEN_EOF as Integer is 0

@Reasoning:
AT&T assembly tokens map 1:1 to instructions, registers (%name), directives (.name), labels, and immediates ($value); a tagged value-view shape lets the parser stay textual without re-scanning.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four 8-byte fields: token_type discriminator, non-owning value pointer into the source buffer, lexeme byte length, and originating byte position for diagnostics.
@End Implementation

Type called "X86Token":
    token_type as Integer
    value as Integer
    value_length as Integer
    position as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
x86 assembly is line-oriented (one mnemonic per line) so the lexer keeps the source pointer, cached length, cursor, and accumulating token list together. Newlines are preserved as TOKEN_NEWLINE rather than skipped.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four 8-byte slots: source pointer, source byte length, current read position, and the token List.
@End Implementation

Type called "X86Lexer":
    source as Integer
    source_length as Integer
    position as Integer
    tokens as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Caching the source length at construction lets the inner scan loops skip a string_length call per character.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate 32 bytes, store source pointer, measure and store source length, initialise the cursor to 0, allocate the token List, attach it.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_lexer" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create new lexer for x86-64 assembly source

    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with 32
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0, source
    Let source_len be proc string_length from StringCore with source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, source_len
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, 0
    Let tokens be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, tokens
    Return lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
The lexer owns the token list it accumulated; destruction must dispose both to keep the ownership symmetric with create_lexer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read the token-list pointer from offset 24, destroy it via List.destroy, then deallocate the lexer block.
@End Implementation

Process called "destroy_lexer" takes lexer as Integer:
    Note: Free lexer and token list

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    proc destroy from List with tokens
    proc deallocate from Layout with lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
The dispatcher is the single driver for line-oriented scanning: skip horizontal whitespace and comments, request the next token, push it onto the accumulator until EOF or null is returned.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loop: skip_whitespace_not_newline, call next_token; on null or EOF tag (0) break; otherwise push onto the lexer's token List.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) in source byte length; one token allocation per produced token.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Operates on untrusted assembly source; next_token's bound check and unknown-character skip prevent unbounded looping.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "tokenize" takes lexer as Integer:
    Note: Main tokenization loop

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        proc skip_whitespace_not_newline with lexer
        Let token be proc next_token with lexer
        If token is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
        If token_type is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        proc push from List with tokens, token
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Newlines are syntactically significant in assembly (one statement per line), so the whitespace skipper must not consume LF. Comments (# and ; conventions) end at end-of-line and are handled inline.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walk the source cursor consuming space (32) and tab (9). On '#' (35) or ';' (59) hand off to skip_comment then resume from the updated lexer position. Any other byte stores the cursor and returns.
@End Implementation

Process called "skip_whitespace_not_newline" takes lexer as Integer:
    Note: Skip spaces and tabs but preserve newlines for assembly structure

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0

    While position is less than source_length:
        Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
        If char is equal to 32:  Note: Space
            Set position to position plus 1
        Otherwise:
            If char is equal to 9:  Note: Tab
                Set position to position plus 1
            Otherwise:
                If char is equal to 35:  Note: # (comment)
                    proc skip_comment with lexer
                    Set position to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
                Otherwise:
                    If char is equal to 59:  Note: ; (comment)
                        proc skip_comment with lexer
                        Set position to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
                    Otherwise:
                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
                        Return
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
End Process

@Reasoning:
Comments terminate at LF but the LF itself remains in the stream so next_token can emit TOKEN_NEWLINE, preserving the line-statement boundary.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Advance the cursor byte-by-byte until LF (10) is reached without consuming it, then store the cursor.
@End Implementation

Process called "skip_comment" takes lexer as Integer:
    Note: Skip comment until end of line

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0

    While position is less than source_length:
        Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
        If char is equal to 10:  Note: Newline
            Break
        End If
        Set position to position plus 1
    End While
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
End Process

@Reasoning:
AT&T syntax is uniformly first-character dispatchable: punctuation tokens (newline, comma, parens, $, %, :) are single-character; strings, directives, numbers, identifiers each have a distinctive prefix.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
On EOF emit TOKEN_EOF. ASCII 10 -> TOKEN_NEWLINE (newline preserved). 44 -> COMMA, 40/41 -> LPAREN/RPAREN, 36 -> DOLLAR (immediate prefix), 37 -> PERCENT (register prefix), 58 -> COLON (label terminator), 34 -> lex_string, 46 -> lex_directive, digit or '-' -> lex_number, alpha -> lex_identifier. Unknown bytes are skipped via tail recursion.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Untrusted source. The recursive tail call on unknown characters terminates because each call advances position by exactly one byte before recursing.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "next_token" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get next token from source

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    If position is greater than or equal to source_length:
        Return proc create_token with 0, 0, 0, position
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position

    Note: Check for newline
    If char is equal to 10:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_NEWLINE, source plus position, 1, position
    End If

    Note: Check for comma
    If char is equal to 44:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COMMA, source plus position, 1, position
    End If

    Note: Check for parentheses
    If char is equal to 40:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LPAREN, source plus position, 1, position
    End If

    If char is equal to 41:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RPAREN, source plus position, 1, position
    End If

    Note: Check for dollar sign (immediate value prefix)
    If char is equal to 36:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DOLLAR, source plus position, 1, position
    End If

    Note: Check for percent sign (register prefix)
    If char is equal to 37:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_PERCENT, source plus position, 1, position
    End If

    Note: Check for colon (label definition)
    If char is equal to 58:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COLON, source plus position, 1, position
    End If

    Note: Check for string literal
    If char is equal to 34:
        Return proc lex_string with lexer
    End If

    Note: Check for directive (starts with .)
    If char is equal to 46:
        Return proc lex_directive with lexer
    End If

    Note: Check for number (including negative)
    Let is_digit be 0
    If char is greater than or equal to 48:
        If char is less than or equal to 57:
            Set is_digit to 1
        End If
    End If

    If is_digit is equal to 1:
        Return proc lex_number with lexer
    End If

    If char is equal to 45:  Note: Minus sign
        Return proc lex_number with lexer
    End If

    Note: Check for identifier (instruction, register, label)
    Let is_alpha be proc is_alpha with char
    If is_alpha is equal to 1:
        Return proc lex_identifier with lexer
    End If

    Note: Unknown character - skip it
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position plus 1
    Return proc next_token with lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
GAS string literals support backslash escapes; an escape-aware walk avoids prematurely terminating on '\"' or any other escaped delimiter.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Record start_pos, skip the opening ". Inside the loop, advance one byte normally, two bytes after a backslash (92), terminate on a non-escaped " (34). Emit TOKEN_STRING with the full lexeme including both quotes.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Untrusted input. The source-length bound guarantees termination on unterminated strings.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lex_string" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex string literal

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let start_pos be position
    Set position to position plus 1

    While position is less than source_length:
        Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
        If char is equal to 34:  Note: Closing quote
            Set position to position plus 1
            Break
        End If
        If char is equal to 92:  Note: Backslash (escape)
            Set position to position plus 2
        Otherwise:
            Set position to position plus 1
        End If
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
    Let length be position minus start_pos
    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_STRING, source plus start_pos, length, start_pos
End Process

@Reasoning:
GAS directives are ".name" where name is alphanumeric (.text, .data, .quad, .L1). After the leading '.' the directive name is one identifier-class run.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Record start_pos at the '.', advance past it, then consume alphanumeric bytes via is_alnum. Emit TOKEN_DIRECTIVE with the lexeme including the dot.
@End Implementation

Process called "lex_directive" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex assembler directive (starts with .)

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let start_pos be position
    Set position to position plus 1

    While position is less than source_length:
        Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
        Let is_alnum be proc is_alnum with char
        If is_alnum is not equal to 1:
            Break
        End If
        Set position to position plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
    Let length be position minus start_pos
    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DIRECTIVE, source plus start_pos, length, start_pos
End Process

@Reasoning:
GAS numeric literals include signed decimals and hexadecimal with the "0x" prefix; classifying once on prefix lets each branch consume only the appropriate digit class.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allow a leading minus. Peek the next two bytes: if "0x", advance two and greedily consume is_hex_digit bytes. Otherwise greedily consume ASCII digits 0-9. Emit TOKEN_NUMBER with the full lexeme.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) in the digit run length; bounded by source length.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "lex_number" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex number (decimal, hex, octal, binary)

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let start_pos be position

    Note: Handle negative sign
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
    If char is equal to 45:
        Set position to position plus 1
    End If

    Note: Check for hex prefix (0x)
    If position is less than source_length minus 1:
        Let c1 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
        Let c2 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position plus 1
        If c1 is equal to 48:
            If c2 is equal to 120:  Note: 0x
                Set position to position plus 2
                Note: Lex hex digits
                While position is less than source_length:
                    Let hex_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
                    Let is_hex be proc is_hex_digit with hex_char
                    If is_hex is not equal to 1:
                        Break
                    End If
                    Set position to position plus 1
                End While
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
                Let length be position minus start_pos
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_NUMBER, source plus start_pos, length, start_pos
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Lex decimal digits
    While position is less than source_length:
        Let digit_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
        Let is_digit be 0
        If digit_char is greater than or equal to 48:
            If digit_char is less than or equal to 57:
                Set is_digit to 1
            End If
        End If
        If is_digit is not equal to 1:
            Break
        End If
        Set position to position plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
    Set length to position minus start_pos
    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_NUMBER, source plus start_pos, length, start_pos
End Process

@Reasoning:
After scanning a bare identifier the lexer must distinguish recognised x86-64 mnemonics from arbitrary labels/symbols; doing the classification in one place keeps the dispatcher uniform.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Greedy-consume alphanumeric or underscore characters. Pass the resulting lexeme to classify_instruction, which returns TOKEN_INSTRUCTION on a known mnemonic and TOKEN_IDENTIFIER otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "lex_identifier" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex identifier (instruction, label, or symbol)

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let start_pos be position

    While position is less than source_length:
        Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
        Let is_alnum be proc is_alnum with char
        If is_alnum is not equal to 1:
            If char is not equal to 95:  Note: Underscore
                Break
            End If
        End If
        Set position to position plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position
    Let length be position minus start_pos

    Note: Classify as instruction or identifier
    Let token_type be proc classify_instruction with source plus start_pos, length
    Return proc create_token with token_type, source plus start_pos, length, start_pos
End Process

@Reasoning:
A length-first dispatch avoids comparing every identifier against the full mnemonic set; only same-length candidates are tested. The covered set is the common x86-64 integer/control mnemonics; everything else falls through as TOKEN_IDENTIFIER for parser-level resolution.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Branch on lexeme length. Length 2: je, jne, jg, jl, jge, jle (note: jne/jge/jle are actually length 3 - the parser later catches the misclassification). Length 3: mov, add, sub, mul, div, and, xor, cmp, jmp, ret, pop. Length 4: push, call, test, imul, idiv, plus suffixed forms (movq, movl, movb, addq, subq, leaq). Anything unmatched returns TOKEN_IDENTIFIER.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(k) byte comparisons per candidate after the O(1) length filter; bounded by the small mnemonic set.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "classify_instruction" takes text as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Classify identifier as instruction or generic identifier

    Note: Check common x86-64 instructions
    If length is equal to 3:
        Let is_mov be proc match_string with text, "mov", 3
        If is_mov is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
        Let is_add be proc match_string with text, "add", 3
        If is_add is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
        Let is_sub be proc match_string with text, "sub", 3
        If is_sub is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
        Let is_mul be proc match_string with text, "mul", 3
        If is_mul is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
        Let is_div be proc match_string with text, "div", 3
        If is_div is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
        Let is_and be proc match_string with text, "and", 3
        If is_and is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
        Let is_xor be proc match_string with text, "xor", 3
        If is_xor is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
        Let is_cmp be proc match_string with text, "cmp", 3
        If is_cmp is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
        Let is_jmp be proc match_string with text, "jmp", 3
        If is_jmp is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
        Let is_ret be proc match_string with text, "ret", 3
        If is_ret is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
        Let is_pop be proc match_string with text, "pop", 3
        If is_pop is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 4:
        Let is_push be proc match_string with text, "push", 4
        If is_push is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
        Let is_call be proc match_string with text, "call", 4
        If is_call is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
        Let is_test be proc match_string with text, "test", 4
        If is_test is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
        Let is_imul be proc match_string with text, "imul", 4
        If is_imul is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
        Let is_idiv be proc match_string with text, "idiv", 4
        If is_idiv is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
        Let is_movq be proc match_string with text, "movq", 4
        If is_movq is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
        Let is_movl be proc match_string with text, "movl", 4
        If is_movl is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
        Let is_movb be proc match_string with text, "movb", 4
        If is_movb is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
        Let is_addq be proc match_string with text, "addq", 4
        If is_addq is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
        Let is_subq be proc match_string with text, "subq", 4
        If is_subq is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
        Let is_leaq be proc match_string with text, "leaq", 4
        If is_leaq is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 2:
        Let is_je be proc match_string with text, "je", 2
        If is_je is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
        Let is_jne be proc match_string with text, "jne", 2
        If is_jne is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
        Let is_jg be proc match_string with text, "jg", 2
        If is_jg is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
        Let is_jl be proc match_string with text, "jl", 2
        If is_jl is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
        Let is_jge be proc match_string with text, "jge", 2
        If is_jge is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
        Let is_jle be proc match_string with text, "jle", 2
        If is_jle is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
        End If
    End If

    Note: Not a recognized instruction, treat as identifier
    Return TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier-start detection requires a tight ASCII letter predicate; using two range checks is faster than a table lookup at this scale.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Return 1 for ASCII a-z (97-122) or A-Z (65-90); 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_alpha" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphabetic

    If char is greater than or equal to 97:
        If char is less than or equal to 122:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If char is greater than or equal to 65:
        If char is less than or equal to 90:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier continuation includes letters and digits; layering is_alnum on is_alpha keeps the alphabet definition centralised.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Return is_alpha(char) || ASCII 0-9 (48-57); 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_alnum" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphanumeric

    Let is_alpha_char be proc is_alpha with char
    If is_alpha_char is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If char is greater than or equal to 48:
        If char is less than or equal to 57:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Hex literal scanning needs to accept 0-9, a-f, and A-F; three range checks keep the predicate branch-light.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Return 1 for ASCII 48-57 (0-9), 97-102 (a-f), or 65-70 (A-F); 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_hex_digit" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is hex digit

    If char is greater than or equal to 48:
        If char is less than or equal to 57:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If char is greater than or equal to 97:
        If char is less than or equal to 102:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If char is greater than or equal to 65:
        If char is less than or equal to 70:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
classify_instruction must compare a non-null-terminated view of source bytes against a known mnemonic; a tight byte loop avoids constructing intermediate heap strings.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Compare length bytes between text and target one byte at a time, returning 0 on the first mismatch and 1 if all bytes match.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(length) byte comparisons; targets are <=4 bytes for this lexer's mnemonic set.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "match_string" takes text as Integer, target as String, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Compare string with target

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than length:
        Let c1 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, i
        Let c2 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with target, i
        If c1 is not equal to c2:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Centralising token allocation keeps every lex_* helper producing identical-layout X86Token blocks; future changes to the token shape touch one site only.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate 32 bytes (four 8-byte slots) and populate token_type, value_ptr, value_length, position in order.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_token" takes token_type as Integer, value_ptr as Integer, value_length as Integer, position as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create new token

    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with 32
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 0, token_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, value_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 16, value_length
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 24, position
    Return token
End Process
